summary: Hi, I'm Josh, the co-founder and CEO of Glyphic Biotechnologies, a VC-funded biotechnology startup commercializing a next-generation protein sequencing platform.  I graduated Phi Beta Kappa, Tau Beta Pi, and Summa Cum Laude from the University of California, San Diego, which I attended fully-funded on the Jacobs School Scholarship. I double majored in Bioengineering: Biotechnology B.S. and General Biology B.S where I was a Barry Goldwater Scholar and the Valedictorian in the Department of Bioengineering. Subsequently, I completed a Master of Translational Medicine degree through the University of California, San Francisco and University of California, Berkeley in the Department of Bioengineering, from where I spun-out my first startup, Nephrosant. Nephrosant has raised over $22M in funding to commercialize a low-cost, non-invasive diagnostic assay for kidney injury. I am currently on leave of absence from the MSTP MD-PhD at the Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine and Department of Biomedical Engineering. I subsequently graduated with an MBA from the Stanford University Graduate School of Business, where I was the Henry Ford II Scholar (Valedictorian), a Siebel Scholar, and an Arjay Miller Scholar.   My first-author, peer-reviewed publications have been published in top-tier journals such as Nature Reviews Genetics and Science Translational Medicine. I am also an inventor on 6 issued/filed patents and author on 18 research articles. I was named to the Forbes 30 Under 30 Healthcare list and awarded a Biocom California Catalyst Award in 2021.  In my free time, I enjoy going to farmer's markets on Sunday mornings, sipping on dirty chai lattes, and creating pastries from scratch.  Personal Website: www.joshuayang.com Google Scholar: https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=D1oXpdIAAAAJ
organization_description_1: Glyphic Biotechnologies is decoding the human proteome through full coverage, de novo protein sequencing at single molecule resolutions, advancing beyond the decades old technologies based on mass spectrometry and ELISAs. This platform will enable the development of novel therapeutics and diagnostics and, ultimately, a deeper understanding of human biology.
organization_description_2: The 21 Fund is a $2M seed fund building and investing in the next generation of Stanford Graduate School of Business (GSB) startups. The mission of The 21 Fund is to be the most hands-on and value-add investor to every GSB ‘21 founder.
organization_description_3: While early detection of kidney diseases saves money and increases therapeutic options, these diagnostics did not exist. Until now. The QSant Assay and Score provides a quantitative measure of kidney injury, detecting injury in its earliest stages and providing a risk score that enables clinicians to intervene. Nephrosant has raised over $22M in funding up through Series A rounds.
